90% of men and women say that abortion service at three to four clinics is satisfactory, while 9% merely say there is a need for higher quality of abortion services [Cahalane and Ferri 2004]

Only 4% of respondents in Portugal agreed that “it is acceptable for a woman to decide to have an abortion when she finds out that the child will be born with a mental / physical disability”, [Cahalane and Ferri 2004]

26% feel that abortion should be allowed as a matter of choice and only 12% feel that abortion should be used on demand - 62% feel that it should not be done at all. A similar discrepancy between bureucrats and politicians has existed in the UK since 1989 [cf. Carrie 1990], indicating that abortion remains highly politicised.
